Southern Dwarf Blueberry, Small Cluster Blueberry - Vaccinium tenellum Aiton (syn. Cyanococcus tenellus) A rather obscure blueberry, grows in rhizomatous clumps and is only 10-40 cm tall. Mostly restricted to xeric woodlands of the Coastal Plain of the Carolinas. Second/third images here shows another stem nearby. Just a few were blooming on 21 March 2024. I had seen them in full bloom 6 April 2023: www.inaturalist.org/observations/154083884 References - Carolina Nature (Will Cook): www.carolinanature.com/trees/vate.html - Porcher and Rayner (Univ. of South Carolina Press, 2001), A Guide to the Wildflowers of South Carolina, p. 245 (photo) - Radford et al., Vascular Flora of the Carolinas (UNC Press, 1968), pp. 814 (key), 815 (description) - Weakley, Flora of the Southeastern United States (UNC Herbarium, 2020), pp. 1183, 1187

occurrenceRemarks: This big clump of low (20 cm) flowering shrubs in dry Sandhills habitat confused me. They had abundant flowers but few leaves. (Some browsed off, perhaps?) I thought they were Lyonia, but no, they appear to be: Southern Dwarf Blueberry, Small Cluster Blueberry - Vaccinium tenellum Aiton (syn. Cyanococcus tenellus) A rather obscure blueberry, grows in rhizomatous clumps and is only 10-40 cm tall. Mostly restricted to xeric woodlands of the Coastal Plain of the Carolinas. My field trip companion, a good botanist, thought they might be blueberries--correct! References - Carolina Nature (Will Cook): www.carolinanature.com/trees/vate.html - NC State University (states invasive, perhaps an error): plants.ces.ncsu.edu/plants/vaccinium-tenellum/ - Porcher and Rayner (Univ. of South Carolina Press, 2001), A Guide to the Wildflowers of South Carolina, p. 245 (photo) - Radford et al., Vascular Flora of the Carolinas (UNC Press, 1968), pp. 814 (key), 815 (description) - Weakley, Flora of the Southeastern United States (UNC Herbarium, 2020), pp. 1183, 1187
